            "text": "Overview Ozone’s presets are designed to give you a quick starting point for mastering your projects.\nRetrieve, store, or customize presets with the Preset Manager System. There are two types Preset Managers as outlined in the image and table below.\n    LABEL TYPE OF PRESET MANAGER DESCRIPTION      Global Preset Manager Includes presets for the Ozone 9 mothership plug-in.    Module Preset Manager Includes presets for an individual module.    Presets in Ozone Plug-ins\nThe Ozone 9 module and component plug-in presets are interchangeable. Ozone 9 Advanced users can make use of their module presets within the component plug-ins and vice versa.\n Updating Module Presets\nThe Module Preset window does not include a Save button. Click the Add button to create a new preset from the module\u0026rsquo;s current settings.\n Input Level and Presets\nSetting your input level is important when selecting presets. The presets will sound drastically different if your input level is too loud or quiet.\n  Access Preset Manager To access the Preset Manager:\n Click the Preset button to bring up the Preset Manager window. Click on a preset to apply the associated parameters to all of the controls in the Ozone plug-in.   The Preset Manager controls are outlined in the table below.\n   PRESET CONTROLS DESCRIPTION      Opens Preset Manager section of Help Documentation.    Creates a new preset based on the current settings.    Deletes the selected preset or preset folder.    Make a new folder in your preset directory.    Allows you to change where Ozone stores preset files.    Updates the currently selected preset to include changes.    Edit Preset Comments and Preset Name\nTo add preset comments or edit preset names:\n To edit to the preset name:  Double-click on a preset name. Edit the text in the inline edit field. Press Enter or Return.   To add comments to the preset:  Click on the comments field. Edit the text in the inline edit field. Press Enter or Return.   \n Special characters in Preset Names\nSome characters such as * or / cannot be used as preset names. If you try to type these characters in the name they will be ignored.\n Dirty state flag ( * )\nAn asterisk ( * ) will appear next to a preset that has been modified but not saved.\n  Apply Working Settings To apply most recent work settings not associated with a preset:\n Access Preset Manager. Select \u0026lt;Working Settings\u0026gt;. Hit Close to exit Preset Manager.   Default Select \u0026lt;Default\u0026gt; to reset all parameters within Ozone 9 to their factory default value.\nCustom Default You can override the factory \u0026lt;Default\u0026gt; preset by selecting any preset as your custom default.\n Right-click on the preset you want to use as your custom \u0026lt;Default\u0026gt; settings. In the context menu, select \u0026ldquo;Set presetName as Default.\u0026rdquo;  Undo Custom Default You can undo your custom \u0026lt;Default\u0026gt; settings by:\n Right-click on any preset in the list. In the context menu, select \u0026ldquo;Reset Default to factory default.\u0026rdquo;   Preset Folder Locations Ozone 9 Elements presets are installed and saved to the following locations by default:\n Windows: C:\\Users\\username\\Documents\\iZotope\\Ozone 9\\Presets Mac: /Users/username/Documents/iZotope/Ozone 9/Presets  Share or Migrate Presets\nPresets are saved as an .xml file on your hard drive. This allows you to easily migrate presets files to another computer or share them with others.\n  Show at Startup By default the preset manager will open automatically at startup. If you do not wish for this to occur, uncheck the “Show at Startup” box at the bottom of the presets window.\n",
            "title": "Preset System",
            "url": "../presets/index.html"
